The Thread Specific Data of libcwd currently (June 2026) works
as follows:

1) A thread receives its `TSD_st` object lazily, when it first calls a
   libcwd function that needs thread specific state. The storage for that
   object is heap storage reached through a C++ `thread_local` pointer owned by
   `TSD_st::instance()`; no pthread key is created and no pthread specific
   lookup is needed.

2) The first call marks the object initialized before it initializes the
   libcwd subsystems. If that initialization path calls back into
   `TSD_st::instance()`, the recursive call therefore reuses the same
   partially initialized object instead of starting a second initialization
   for the same thread.

3) The first observed thread initializes only the threading part of its TSD.
   Later threads additionally allocate and initialize the per-debug-object
   TSD for the debug objects that already exist.

4) When a worker thread exits, the C++ runtime destroys a thread-local cleanup
   guard. That guard deletes the worker thread's `TSD_st`; its destructor
   releases per-debug-object TSD, disables the corresponding debug-object slots
   first so recursive diagnostics do not reuse freed objects, and marks the
   persistent thread-list entry as terminating.

5) The main thread's `TSD_st` is intentionally retained until process
   termination. This preserves libcwd diagnostics from global and shared-object
   destructors that can run after the C++ runtime has started tearing down
   thread-local objects.

Version 2's portable C++ code does not provide an equivalent for the version 1
pthread trick that reinstalled a key several times to run libcwd cleanup after
other pthread key destructors. Code that emits libcwd diagnostics from other
thread-local or native key destructors must therefore not rely on libcwd cleanup
being delayed to the last possible native destructor iteration.
